Gauteng has seen its biggest spike in active COVID-19 cases and hospitalised patients yet, amid the first week of level three lockdown.This is according to Premier David Makhura. He says hotspots in Gauteng continue to move around. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Gauteng has seen its biggest spike in active COVID-19 cases and hospitalised patients yet, amid the first week of level three lockdown. This is according to Premier David Makhura. He says hotspots in Gauteng continue to move around. One of the biggest concerns is Johannesburg's inner city. WATCH: Gauteng hotspots could be moved to higher levels The area has contributed the majority of new COVID-19 cases in the province in the last seven days. The West Rand, Tshwane, and Ekurhuleni are also seeing spikes. Gauteng is boasting that it's screened 6,6 million people and tested over 200,000. WATCH: Ramaphosa's visit to Western Cape The province is also mourning two health workers who have recently died from the virus. The main concern now is the rising number of people needing hospitalisation. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.